===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|croke|lang=enm}}, {{term|crok|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} *{{term||crōc|hook, bend, crook|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*krōkaz||bend, hook}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*greg-||tracery, basket, bend}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|kreuk||a bend, fold, wrinkle|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|kroke|lang=gml}}, {{term|krake||fold, wrinkle|lang=gml}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|krog||crook, hook|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|krok||crook, hook|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|krókur||hook|lang=is}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

#A [[bend]]; [[turn]]; [[curve]]; [[curvature]]; a [[flexure]].
#:{{ux|en|She held the baby in the '''crook''' of her arm.}}
#*{{w|Thomas Phaer}} (c.1510-1560)
#*:through lanes, and '''crooks''', and darkness
#A bending of the knee; a [[genuflection]].
#A [[bent]] or curved part; a curving piece or portion (of anything).
#:{{ux|en|the '''crook''' of a cane}}
#*{{RQ:Chmbrs YngrSt|I}}
#*:It was flood-tide along Fifth Avenue; motor, brougham, and victoria swept by on the glittering current; pretty women glanced out from limousine and tonneau; young men of his own type, silk-hatted, frock-coated, the '''crooks'' of their walking sticks tucked up under their left arms, passed on the Park side.
#{{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[lock]] or [[curl]] of hair.
#{{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[gibbet]].
#{{lb|en|obsolete}} A support beam consisting of a post with a cross-beam resting upon it; a bracket or truss consisting of a vertical piece, a horizontal piece, and a strut.
#A shepherd's crook; a [[staff]] with a semi-circular bend ("hook") at one end used by [[shepherd]]s.
#*'''1970''', ''The New English Bible with the Apocrypha, Oxford Study Edition'', published 1976, Oxford University Press, ''Psalms'' 23-4, p.583:
#*:Even though I walk through a / valley dark as death / I fear no evil, for thou art with me, / thy staff and thy '''crook''' are my / comfort.
#A bishop's staff of office.
#An [[artifice]]; a [[trick]]; a [[contrivance]].
#*{{w|Thomas Cranmer}} (1489-1556)
#*:for all your brags, hooks, and '''crooks'''
#A person who steals, lies, cheats or does other dishonest or illegal things; a criminal.
#*'''1973''' November 17, {{w|Richard Nixon}}, reported 1973 November 18, ''The Washington Post'', [http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/watergate/articles/111873-1.htm ''Nixon Tells Editors, ‘I'm Not a Crook’''],
#*:"People have got to know whether or not their President is a '''crook'''. Well, I′m not a '''crook'''. I′ve earned everything I′ve got."
#A [[pothook]].
#*Sir {{w|Walter Scott}} (1771-1832)
#*:as black as the '''crook'''
#{{lb|en|music}} A small tube, usually curved, applied to a trumpet, horn, etc., to change its pitch or key.

